name: architecture-decisions
description: Document the "why" behind technical decisions using Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)

# Purpose
Create searchable, permanent records of significant technical decisions. Answer "why did we do this?" for your future self and team.

# When to use
Use this skill when:
- Choosing between technologies or approaches
- Making tradeoffs (performance vs simplicity, etc.)
- Deviating from conventions
- Making decisions that will be hard to reverse
- Someone asks "why is it like this?"
- Starting a new feature or system

# Inputs
- Decision context (what problem are you solving?)
- Options considered
- Constraints (time, resources, requirements)
- Stakeholders affected

# Output Format (ADR Template)

```markdown
# ADR-{number}: {Title}

## Status
{Proposed | Accepted | Deprecated | Superseded by ADR-X}

## Date
{YYYY-MM-DD}

## Context
{What is the issue? Why does this decision need to be made?}
{What forces are at play? Technical, business, team constraints?}

## Decision
{What is the change that we're proposing and/or doing?}
{State the decision clearly and definitively.}

## Options Considered

### Option 1: {Name}
- Pros: 
- Cons:
- Effort:

### Option 2: {Name}
- Pros:
- Cons:
- Effort:

## Consequences

### Positive
- {What becomes easier?}

### Negative
- {What becomes harder? What debt do we accept?}

### Neutral
- {What changes but is neither good nor bad?}

## References
- {Links to docs, discussions, related ADRs}
```

# When to Write an ADR

## Always Document
- Technology/framework choices
- Database schema decisions
- API design decisions
- Authentication/security approach
- State management architecture
- Third-party service selections
- Breaking changes to existing patterns

## Consider Documenting
- Significant refactoring approaches
- Performance optimization strategies
- Testing strategy decisions
- Deployment/infrastructure choices
- Code organization changes

## Skip Documenting
- Obvious choices (using Dart for Flutter)
- Reversible decisions (variable naming)
- Standard patterns (using async/await)

# ADR Quality Checklist

## Context Section
- [ ] Problem statement is clear
- [ ] Constraints are explicit
- [ ] Assumptions are stated
- [ ] Scope is defined

## Decision Section
- [ ] Decision is unambiguous
- [ ] Rationale is explained
- [ ] Connection to context is clear

## Options Section
- [ ] At least 2 options considered
- [ ] "Do nothing" considered if applicable
- [ ] Pros/cons are honest (not biased)
- [ ] Effort/risk estimated

## Consequences Section
- [ ] Positive outcomes listed
- [ ] Negative tradeoffs acknowledged
- [ ] Impact on future decisions noted

# ADR Storage and Organization

## File Location
```
docs/
└── adr/
    ├── README.md           # Index of all ADRs
    ├── 0001-use-supabase.md
    ├── 0002-state-management-riverpod.md
    ├── 0003-feature-module-structure.md
    └── templates/
        └── adr-template.md
```

## Naming Convention
- `{NNNN}-{short-description}.md`
- Use lowercase, hyphens
- Sequential numbering
- Keep titles short but descriptive

## Index File (README.md)
```markdown
# Architecture Decision Records

| Number | Title | Status | Date |
|--------|-------|--------|------|
| 0001 | Use Supabase for backend | Accepted | 2024-01-15 |
| 0002 | Use Riverpod for state | Accepted | 2024-01-20 |
| 0003 | Feature module structure | Accepted | 2024-02-01 |
```

# Example ADRs

## Example 1: Technology Choice

```markdown
# ADR-0001: Use Supabase for Backend

## Status
Accepted

## Date
2024-01-15

## Context
We need a backend for our dating app MVP. Requirements:
- Real-time messaging
- User authentication
- File storage (photos)
- Fast time-to-market (solo developer)
- Reasonable cost at scale

## Decision
Use Supabase as our backend-as-a-service platform.

## Options Considered

### Option 1: Supabase
- Pros: Real-time built-in, Postgres (powerful), generous free tier, good Flutter SDK
- Cons: Vendor lock-in, less control than self-hosted
- Effort: Low (managed service)

### Option 2: Firebase
- Pros: Very mature, excellent docs, Google backing
- Cons: NoSQL (Firestore) less flexible for complex queries, pricing unpredictable
- Effort: Low

### Option 3: Self-hosted (Postgres + custom API)
- Pros: Full control, no vendor lock-in
- Cons: Significant development time, must handle scaling
- Effort: High

## Consequences

### Positive
- Can focus on app features instead of backend infrastructure
- Real-time subscriptions work out of the box
- RLS provides security at database level

### Negative
- Tied to Supabase's roadmap and pricing
- Some advanced Postgres features may not be exposed
- Must work within their edge function constraints

## References
- https://supabase.com/docs
- Comparison: https://supabase.com/alternatives/supabase-vs-firebase
```

## Example 2: Architecture Decision

```markdown
# ADR-0003: Feature Module Structure

## Status
Accepted

## Date
2024-02-01

## Context
As the app grows, we need a consistent way to organize code. Currently:
- Some features are in `lib/screens/`
- Some are in `lib/features/`
- Business logic is mixed with UI
- Hard to find where code lives

## Decision
Adopt a feature-first module structure with clean architecture layers:
- `features/{name}/data/` - repositories, DTOs
- `features/{name}/domain/` - entities, interfaces
- `features/{name}/presentation/` - screens, widgets, state

## Options Considered

### Option 1: Feature modules (chosen)
- Pros: Scalable, clear ownership, easy to find code
- Cons: More files, some duplication possible
- Effort: Medium (need to migrate existing code)

### Option 2: Layer-first (screens/, services/, models/)
- Pros: Simple, familiar
- Cons: Doesn't scale, features spread across folders
- Effort: Low

### Option 3: Keep current (mixed)
- Pros: No migration effort
- Cons: Inconsistent, gets worse over time
- Effort: None

## Consequences

### Positive
- Clear place for new code
- Features can be developed independently
- Easier to test in isolation

### Negative
- Need to migrate existing code (2-3 days)
- Team needs to learn the pattern
- Some shared code needs careful placement

## References
- ADR-0002 (Riverpod - affects state layer)
- Clean Architecture: https://blog.cleancoder.com/uncle-bob/2012/08/13/the-clean-architecture.html
```

# Updating ADRs

## When to Update
- Status changes (Proposed → Accepted)
- Decision is superseded by new ADR
- Clarifications needed (not changing decision)

## Never Change
- Original decision text
- Original date
- Original reasoning

## How to Supersede
1. Create new ADR with new decision
2. Update old ADR status: "Superseded by ADR-XXXX"
3. Link new ADR to old for context

# Team Practices

## When to Discuss
- Before major technology choices
- Before irreversible decisions
- When team disagrees on approach

## Review Process
1. Draft ADR with status "Proposed"
2. Share with team for review
3. Discuss tradeoffs
4. Update and set status to "Accepted"
5. Commit to repo

## Lightweight Mode (Solo Dev)
- Write shorter ADRs
- Skip formal review
- Focus on capturing "why" for future you
- Still valuable for your future self

# Anti-Patterns

- Writing ADRs after the fact without honest tradeoffs
- ADRs that justify pre-made decisions (fake options)
- Too much detail (ADR should be < 1 page)
- Never referencing ADRs when questions arise
- Treating ADRs as unchangeable law (they're records, not rules)
